did.head: DESCRIPTIVE SUMMARY
did.repository: Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections, Cornell University Library
did.abstract: Collection consists of Jones' records related to golf course design. Includes correspondence, personal material, business records, photographs, sketches, and golf course plans.

bioghist.head: BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE
bioghist.p: Robert Trent Jones (1906-2000) was a golf course architect. Born in Ince-in-Makerfield, England, he grew up in East Rochester, New York, where he became an avid golfer from his youth. Jones attended Cornell University, where he created his own course of study to become a professional golf course designer. During his professional career, he designed and re-designed more than 500 golf courses nationally and internationally, including 79 courses that were used for the United States Open or other national championships. Jones was a founding member and a former president of the American Society of Golf Course Architects. He won numerous awards for his designs and was the first architect inducted into the World Golf Hall of Fame in 1987.

scopecontent.head: COLLECTION DESCRIPTION
scopecontent.p: Collection consists of Jones' records related to golf course design. Includes correspondence, personal material, business records, photographs, sketches, and golf course plans.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions:
accessrestrict.p: Selected boxes and folders containing individuals' financial or other sensitive information are restricted. All boxes in the subseries Financial Records and Legal Affairs are restricted, including boxes 9, 14, 16, 18, 20, 26, 33, 53, 49-54, 56, 58, 60-61, 71-74, 78, 81, 116, 125-126, 135-136, 139-141, 144, 151-152, 171, 177, 197, 199, 219, 239, 249, and 301. Please refer to the collection finding aid for additional restricted folders.

userestrict.head: Use/Reproduction Restrictions:
userestrict.p: Use of the Robert Trent Jones Papers is restricted to non-commercial research and scholarly purposes only and unauthorized use or duplication for commercial purposes may violate the intellectual property rights of Robert Trent Jones, Sr.'s, heirs and assigns.
